{"type":"message","id":"c1d0b16c","parentId":"8cc4ca35","timestamp":"2026-04-15T02:48:11.618Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see - all the errors are about `new mongoose.Types.ObjectId(x)` taking 1 argument when TypeScript expects 0. This is because in mongoose 5.x, the `Types.ObjectId` class extends `SchemaType`, and `SchemaType` constructor signature is `new (path: string, options?: object)`. So the TypeScript types say `ObjectId` constructor takes a path (string) and options (optional object).\n\nBut the error says \"Expected 0 arguments\". That's strange. Unless the TypeScript being used is a different version of the @types.\n\nWait - I think I understand. In mongoose 5.x, the `ObjectId` class's constructor signature for creating an instance should be `new ObjectId(value?: string | number | ObjectId)`. \n\nThe issue might be that TypeScript is inferring `new mongoose.Types.ObjectId` as the schema type constructor instead of the object ID value constructor - they're technically the same class but used differently. I could work around this by using `mongoose.Types.ObjectId.isValid(x) && mongoose.Types.ObjectId(x)` or the newer `mongoose.Types.ObjectId.createById(x)` API instead.\n\nActually, the most straightforward fix is just casting to `any` when calling the constructor, or I could install compatible type definitions. Looking at the actual codebase though, the older code used `mongoose.Types.ObjectId(csId)` without the `new` keyword, which might be the pattern already established here.","thinkingSignature":"a62543725a5f4c18b90232c1dcd14f555d8ea464a2f49d4bf1430d798f1c67bb"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_aoeeb4txoh01_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"new mongoose.Types.ObjectId\\|\\.Types\\.ObjectId\\|Types.ObjectId\" /root/.openclaw/workspaces/ahv-driving-training-system/ahv-dtlx-backend/src/modules/lessons/lessons.service.ts | wc -l\ngrep -n \"mongoose.Types.ObjectId\\b\" /root/.openclaw/work