{"type":"message","id":"78d91717","parentId":"5da9640c","timestamp":"2026-04-15T02:48:47.780Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, so `SchemaType` constructor takes `(path: string, options?: any, instance?: string)`. That means `new mongoose.Types.ObjectId(path)` should work with 1 argument. But the TypeScript error says \"Expected 0 arguments\". \n\nWait - could this be an issue with how the TypeScript compiler is resolving `mongoose.Types.ObjectId`? In mongoose 5.x, `Schema.Types.ObjectId` has the constructor `(path: string, options?)`. But `mongoose.Types.ObjectId` also serves as the value constructor for creating ObjectId instances in JavaScript.\n\nLet me check if there's a separate `ObjectId` value type vs the `ObjectId` SchemaType class. \n\nAh, I see it now—`mongoose.Types.ObjectId` and `Schema.Types.ObjectId` are the same class, so calling `new mongoose.Types.ObjectId(\"...\")` to instantiate a value should technically work, but TypeScript's type definition might be treating it as the SchemaType variant instead of the utility value class.\n\nThe real issue is likely that this codebase is mixing patterns—some places use the newer `new mongoose.Types.ObjectId()` approach while others use the older static method, and the TypeScript definitions haven't caught up with this inconsistency. I should check the tsconfig to see if strict mode or a version mismatch is causing the type checker to reject this pattern.","thinkingSignature":"56ce4c3b93ba8ebfdf77c84b83f49317ccc3edf07bf64753a9777e2cd5fc2f57"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_u8of43izg21r_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /root/.openclaw/workspaces/ahv-driving-training-system/ahv-dtlx-backend/tsconfig.json","workdir":"/root/.openclaw/workspaces/ahv-driving-training-system/ahv-dtlx-backend"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":414,"output":359,"cacheRead":49384,"cacheWrite":489,"totalTokens":506