{"type":"message","id":"4238d2cf","parentId":"4188b633","timestamp":"2026-04-15T02:49:16.165Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Column 62 is `c` from `new mongoose.Types.ObjectId(csId)`. The opening parenthesis `(` is at column 61. So the error is at `new mongoose.Types.ObjectId(csId)` - specifically at the constructor call.\n\nActually wait - the TypeScript compiler reports the error position as the location of the issue, and \"Expected 0 arguments, but got 1\" typically refers to the function being called. The position at column 62 would be at `csId`. But `csId` is the argument being passed. The function is `mongoose.Types.ObjectId` constructor.\n \nLet me reconsider - the error at column 62 points right to `csId`, the argument being passed. TypeScript is saying the constructor expects no arguments at all, which means `mongoose.Types.ObjectId` might not be recognized as a constructor or the type definitions are treating it differently than expected.\n\nLooking at how mongoose's type system works, there's `mongoose.Types.ObjectId` as a utility class for creating ObjectId values, and there's also `Schema.Types.ObjectId` which is a different class entirely. The problem might be that the type definition file is conflating these two, or `mongoose.Types.ObjectId` is resolving to the SchemaType variant instead of the utility class. With `skipLibCheck` enabled, the compiler should still validate constructor calls, so the issue is likely in how the types are being resolved or exported from the library.\n\nSince the current code is failing but this was working before the merge, I need to trace back through the changes to see if the tsconfig was modified or if the code itself shifted from using `mongoose.Types.ObjectId()` to `new mongoose.Types.ObjectId()`.","thinkingSignature":"b4279cf7800e2dfe28e3040e90ecf11a32cb9de7ac0062ff926a99bc313fc440"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_wxol44sgxuzq_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"